{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"914a5a29-91e4-46c5-aff9-eabbed2d5634","content":"Here's the mapping from VSTest → Microsoft.Testing.Platform flags:\n\n| VSTest flag | MTP equivalent | Required package |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` | `--treenode-filter \"/**/TestClass[Category=Integration]\"` | *(built-in)* |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**New command** (MTP args go after `--`):\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --treenode-filter \"/**/TestClass[Category=Integration]\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Project prerequisites** (`.csproj`):\n\n1. Add the four NuGet extension packages listed above.\n2. Enable MTP integration for `dotnet test` on .NET 8:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n> **Tip:** If you want to keep the old `--filter` trait syntax during migration, you can add `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.VSTestBridge`, which lets you pass `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` unchanged. The native `--treenode-filter` syntax is recommended long-term.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1bbc039a-153e-4ebc-8b08-8115e9d7dd0c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling - I can answer this directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me think about the mapping:\n\n**Original command:**\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" --logger trx --collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\" --blame-crash --blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents:**\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the CLI switches change. The key differences:\n\n\n- The `--filter` argument still works for backward compatibility, though the new runner also supports `--treenode-filter` for more advanced filtering\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` (requires the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package)\n- Code coverage collection changes to `--collect code-coverage` with `--report-cobertura`, or you can use the `Microsoft.CodeCoverage` package directly for more control\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the test app becomes its own executable, but `dotnet test` still works as a wrapper that orchestrates the runner. When using `dotnet test` with this platform, the command-line arguments get passed through to the underlying test executable, so most of the familiar flags still function, though some require additional NuGet packages to enable their corresponding output formats. With `dotnet test`, I can pass Microsoft.Testing.Platform arguments after the `--` separator, using the new flag names like `--treenode-filter` for filtering, `--report-trx` for test results, and the coverage/dump options. I'm reconsidering whether the VSTest filter syntax still works through a compatibility layer or if I need to use the new platform-specific syntax.\n\nFor the cleanest migration path, I'd set `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in the project file so `dotnet test` properly recognizes and forwards to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, then add the necessary extension packages like `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` for the specific features needed.","outputTokens":1804,"requestId":"5C2D:2BFBA0:AB37B:D644F:69F54B24"},"id":"6411c483-85a4-4647-8470-f2a538381944","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:54:30.667Z","parentId":"cbd937db-8e7f-4ab9-80c8-ca34b251e5d2"}
